## Running the project — CRITICAL

**NEVER start the app directly** with `npm start`, `npx ts-node`, `node dist/index.js`, or any direct execution.
**ALWAYS use `vibew dev`** — it starts the app behind the VibeWarden sidecar with TLS,
rate limiting, security headers, and all configured protections active.

```bash
vibew dev          # Start dev environment (app + sidecar + dependencies)
vibew dev --watch  # Start with hot reload on config changes
vibew status       # Check component health
vibew doctor       # Diagnose common issues (run this when something breaks)
```

The app runs on port {{ .Port }} internally, but **always access it through the sidecar
at https://localhost:8443**. Never expose port {{ .Port }} directly.

Running the app without the sidecar means NO TLS, NO auth, NO rate limiting, NO WAF.
This is a security risk even in development.

## Testing

```bash
npm test                  # Run all tests
npm test -- --watch       # Watch mode
npm run build             # Compile TypeScript
npm run lint              # Run ESLint
npm run lint:fix          # Auto-fix lint issues
```

### Testing authenticated endpoints

When auth is enabled:

```bash
vibew token                                         # Generate a dev JWT
vibew token --email test@example.com --role admin   # Custom claims
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $(vibew token)" https://localhost:8443/api/...
```

### Working with secrets

Never hardcode secrets. Use vibew:

```bash
vibew secret set DB_PASSWORD "secret123"   # Store a secret
vibew secret get DB_PASSWORD               # Retrieve a secret
vibew secret list                          # List all secrets
```

Access secrets from code via environment variables — vibew injects them at startup.

## TypeScript idioms to follow

1. **Strict mode**: The project uses `"strict": true` in `tsconfig.json`. Every
   type must be explicit — avoid `any`
   ```typescript
   // Bad
   function handle(req: any, res: any): void { ... }

   // Good
   import { Request, Response } from "express";
   function handle(req: Request, res: Response): void { ... }
   ```

2. **Interface-based ports**: Define domain contracts as TypeScript interfaces
   in `src/ports/`, not next to implementations
   ```typescript
   // src/ports/user-repository.ts
   export interface UserRepository {
     findById(id: string): Promise<User | null>;
     save(user: User): Promise<void>;
   }
   ```

3. **Readonly**: Prefer `readonly` properties on value objects and domain types
   ```typescript
   interface User {
     readonly id: string;
     readonly email: string;
     readonly createdAt: Date;
   }
   ```

4. **Discriminated unions**: Model exhaustive domain states without stringly-typed
   booleans
   ```typescript
   type AuthResult =
     | { readonly kind: "success"; readonly userId: string }
     | { readonly kind: "unauthenticated" }
     | { readonly kind: "error"; readonly cause: Error };
   ```

5. **Never use `any`**: Use `unknown` for truly unknown types, then narrow
   ```typescript
   function parsePayload(raw: unknown): Payload {
     if (typeof raw !== "object" || raw === null) {
       throw new Error("invalid payload");
     }
     // narrow further...
   }
   ```

6. **Async/await over callbacks**: Use `async`/`await` for all asynchronous code;
   avoid `.then()` chains
   ```typescript
   app.get("/items", async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
     const items = await repository.findAll();
     res.json(items);
   });
   ```

7. **ESLint + Prettier**: Run `npm run lint:fix` before every commit. Lint
   errors fail the CI check

## Directory layout

```
src/
  domain/       # Entities, value objects, domain events — no framework imports
  ports/        # Interfaces (inbound + outbound)
  adapters/     # Implementations of ports (Express, database, etc.)
  app/          # Application services (use cases — orchestrate, no business logic)
  index.ts      # Entry point — wires everything together
```

## Security — DO NOT IMPLEMENT

**Security is handled by vibew — do NOT implement TLS/auth/rate-limiting/WAF in app code.**

The VibeWarden sidecar handles:

- Authentication middleware (sidecar handles it via Ory Kratos)
- Rate limiting (sidecar handles it)
- TLS configuration (sidecar handles it)
- Security headers (sidecar injects them)

When auth is enabled, read user identity from headers injected by the sidecar:

```typescript
const userId    = req.headers["x-user-id"] as string | undefined;
const userEmail = req.headers["x-user-email"] as string | undefined;
const verified  = req.headers["x-user-verified"] === "true";
```

## Adding dependencies

Check license before adding any dependency:
- Approved: Apache 2.0, MIT, BSD-2, BSD-3
- Rejected: GPL, AGPL, LGPL, CC-BY-SA, proprietary

```bash
npm install <package>          # Runtime dependency
npm install --save-dev <package>  # Dev-only dependency
```

## vibew CLI Reference

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `vibew dev` | Start dev environment (generates config, starts stack) |
| `vibew dev --watch` | Start with file watching and hot reload |
| `vibew status` | Show health of all components |
| `vibew logs` | Tail logs from all services |
| `vibew logs app` | Tail logs from app only |
| `vibew doctor` | Diagnose common issues |
| `vibew token` | Generate a dev JWT for testing |
| `vibew token --email u@example.com --role admin` | Generate JWT with custom claims |
| `vibew secret get NAME` | Get a secret value |
| `vibew secret set NAME VALUE` | Set a secret value |
| `vibew secret list` | List all secrets |
| `vibew cert export` | Export TLS certificate for trust anchoring |
| `vibew validate` | Validate vibewarden.yaml |
| `vibew add auth` | Enable Ory Kratos authentication |
| `vibew add postgres` | Add PostgreSQL database |
| `vibew eject` | Eject to raw Docker Compose (advanced, one-way) |
| `vibew generate` | Regenerate runtime config from vibewarden.yaml |

## Common tasks

### Add a new HTTP endpoint

1. Add route handler in `src/index.ts` (or extract to a router module)
2. Define request/response types as TypeScript interfaces
3. Add test in `src/index.test.ts`
4. Run `vibew dev` to test

### Add a new domain entity

1. Create file in `src/domain/`
2. Define as an interface with `readonly` properties (value object) or a class (entity)
3. Keep domain types free of Express/framework imports
4. Add unit tests next to the source file
